column5: Probably the hardest race of my life. I'm not really sure what happened to me - but something happened - most likely nutrition related in the hours and days leading up to the race. I had wild indigestion in the 2 hours before the gun went off. My stomach was not happy. By the start, however, I felt ok - only a slight stiffness in my GI. The first half marathon felt fantastic. The pace easy, the crowd elated, and plenty of athletes running similar paces. I was feeling good, even, and was hydrating and fueling. The race peaked as I ran through the infamous wave of wellesley college girls. The deafening screaming and endless row of hands extended had me delivering strings of high fives at 5:5x pace. After the half way, my body changed in a big way. All of a sudden it became a strain to run 6:20-6:30 pace. I fought from miles 13 - 16. By the time I hit mile 18 I wasn't sure I was going to make it to the end - I had nothing left. I had to stop and walk at a Gatorade station in an attempt to recover - I became cold and was shivering as I started to run again. I picked up a space blanket and ran like superman the last 8 miles on the course. Running 7-8 min pace was extremely difficult. I'm very glad I was able to make it across that finish line. The interesting thing was that I never felt uncomfortable aerobically on the course - breathing was controlled - and after I crashed extreme fatigue took over my body.
